UK: Wards in Glasgow Hospitals Closed by Norovirus Infection
---------------------------------------------------------------
GLASGOW: Eight wards at a Glasgow hospital and an elderly care unit have
been shut to new admissions following a further outbreak of [norovirus
infection]. The virus has now spread to 6 wards at the Victoria Infirmary
and 2 wards at its Mansionhouse Unit, a facility caring for pensioners. A
ward at the Western Infirmary has also been closed by [norovirus infection].
Five wards at the Victoria in the south side were closed at the weekend
because of the outbreak and 15 patients were showing symptoms. Now 28
patients are thought to have the virus. None are giving cause for concern.
Around 220 pensioners are cared for at the Mansionhouse Unit. The wards
closed have 3 or more patients who have suffered diarrhoea and vomiting. A
spokesman for NHS Greater Glasgow said: "The normal extra infection control
precautions have been put in place. "The wards have been closed as a
precautionary measure."
Winter vomiting disease is caused by a highly infectious virus and has been
responsible for closing scores of hospital wards and nursing homes. It
spreads quickly through the air and usually causes about 48 hours of
sickness, fever and diarrhoea. Incidents of [norovirus infection] trebled
in 2002 and experts fear new and more virulent strains have now appeared.
It was also confirmed the North Glasgow Trust has taken the precautionary
step of closing a ward to new admissions at the Western following a small
outbreak of [norovirus infection]. Six patients and one member of staff are
showing symptoms. The 21 bedded ward currently has 20 patients. A trust
spokesman said: "Our infection control team is working closely with the
ward and the situation is being constantly monitored."
The ward closures come a few months after 8 wards had to be shut in another
area of the Victoria Infirmary. A ward at a second hospital, the Southern
General, was also closed. The Victoria Infirmary was also hit in Aug 2003,
and Oct 2002. And - in one of the worst outbreaks of its kind - in Jan
2002, the hospital had to shut 12 wards, 8 of them in the Mansionhouse
Unit, after more than 100 people contracted infection.
