Source: Eurosurveillance Weekly, Volume 8, Issue 11, Thu 11 Mar 2004 [edited]
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ew/2004/040311.asp>

Viral Gastroenteritis Epidemic of 2002 Associated with New Norovirus Variant
----------------------------------------------------------------------------
Public health workers from around Europe will recall 2002/2003 as the
'winter of norovirus outbreaks'. Noroviruses are the most common cause of
gastroenteritis in the community and are often associated with outbreaks in
semi-closed environments such as nursing homes, hospitals, cruise ships and
hotels. Reports in medical channels including Promed-mail
(<http://www.promedmail.org>), Eurosurveillance Weekly (1), and the popular
press brought an apparent epidemic of this common viral cause of
gastroenteritis to public attention. As was recently reported in The
Lancet, the European Foodborne Viruses Network
(<http://www.eufoodborneviruses.net>/), a research and surveillance group
funded by the European Commission Directorate-General for Research, has
been able to systematically confirm the Europe-wide increase of viral
gastroenteritis outbreaks and show that the increase in outbreaks in this
period was associated with the emergence of a new norovirus variant (a
genogroup II4 virus) (2).
Three of the participants in the network, the Netherlands, Germany and
England and Wales, had sustained epidemiological and viral characterisation
surveillance from 1995 to 2002. All three of these regions noted an
aberrant summertime peak and an unprecedented wintertime epidemic which
followed the detection of a new norovirus variant with a consistent
mutation in the polymerase gene. Eight out of nine countries with historic
trend data observed a substantial increase in norovirus outbreaks in 2002
over the previous peak from 1995 to 2001. Following initial detection of
the new variant in January 2002 in the Netherlands and Germany, the virus
spread and was the predominant cause of outbreaks throughout Europe. In the
six countries that collected data on the setting of these outbreaks, 60 to
85 percent occurred in healthcare settings (hospitals, nursing homes and
residential homes).
These findings highlight the dynamic nature of norovirus epidemiology. Even
within the predominant genogroup II4, new strains are capable of emerging
and causing major public health impact. These observations raise more
questions than they answer. For example, what characteristic of the 'new
variant' drove the epidemic? Is the virus more stable in the environment?
Did its antigenicity change such that it escaped existing immunity in the
population? And, how do these viruses spread so rapidly? It is often said
that international borders do not deter infectious diseases. The
dissemination of this epidemic also demonstrates just how rapidly
noroviruses can spread. This is not the first time that an international
epidemic has been associated with a common strain (3) and therefore
surveillance which combines basic public health data with virological
characterisation is essential to furthering understanding noroviruses, and
ultimately, for controlling them.
(By Ben Lopman, Health Protection Agency Communicable Disease Surveillance
Centre, London, England, on behalf of the European Foodborne Viruses Network.)
References:
(1) Feely E, McKeown P, Pedalino B. Gastroenteritis in holidaymakers
returning from Andorra, January-February 2002. Eurosurveillance Weekly
2002: 6(10): 07/3/2002. (<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ew/2002/020307.asp>)
(2) Lopman B, Vennema H, Kohli E, Pothier P, Sanchez A, Negredo A et al.
Increase in viral gastroenteritis outbreaks in Europe and epidemic spread
of new norovirus variant. Lancet 2004;363:682-8.
(3) Noel JS, Fankhauser RL, Ando T, Monroe SS, Glass RI. Identification of
a distinct common strain of "Norwalk-like viruses" having a global
distribution. J Infect Dis 1999;179:1334-44.
