Source: Anchorage Daily News, Sat 13 Mar 2004 [edited]
<http://www.adn.com/sports/story/4846175p-4782980c.html

USA: Norovirus Outbreak Affects Sled Dog Race in Alaska
--------------------------------------------------------
State health officials mingled with mushers, race officials and visitors on
the trail of the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race trying to nip in the bud an
outbreak of highly contagious norovirus infection. Dr. Joe McLaughlin, an
epidemiologist with the state Department of Health, said a dozen cases have
been traced to McGrath, but the illness has traveled to Anchorage and the
village of Ruby. He flew to several race checkpoints on Fri 12 Mar 2004 to
track down fresh cases and to try to stop it from spreading further --
particularly striving to prevent it from affecting mushers.
"Severe bouts can lead to dehydration," he said. "That's why it's such a
concern among the athletes" who already may be dehydrated from their race.
Formerly known as Norwalk virus, norovirus causes vomiting, nausea and
diarrhea. Outbreaks often occur where large numbers of people mingle, such
as on cruise ships and tour buses, and is passed by eating or drinking food
or water contaminated by an infected person. The bouts typically last a day
or two, McLaughlin said, and there is no treatment. Most people recover
within two or three days.
The race outbreak seems to have started in McGrath in late February,
McLaughlin said. Several Iditarod staff members and volunteers from
Anchorage visited McGrath to help coordinate the race and returned showing
symptoms of the virus. Eventually, 11 people were diagnosed, he said. When
a physician's assistant in McGrath reported on The 11 Mar 2004 that
additional cases were showing up, McLaughlin said, concern quickly
elevated. The doctor, representing the Section of Epidemiology, and staff
of the Department of Environmental Conservation flew to McGrath to
investigate, and the federal Centers for Disease Control assigned a person
to the Alaska outbreak.
McLaughlin walked among the crowd gathered outside the Ruby checkpoint,
asking if anyone had the symptoms. No mushers have been affected, he said,
but two volunteer veterinarians in Ruby contracted it. Race officials are
now helping monitor mushers and the army of volunteers who help put on the
race every year, McLaughlin said. "We're in active surveillance," he said.
His advice to people along the trail was to wash their hands thoroughly and
often.
(By Joel Gay)
